  <h1>About</h1>
  <p>夜食 — <em>yashoku</em> — means a late-night meal. Not dinner. Not a snack. The specific thing you eat after the last train, under a tarpaulin, in a city that hasn't stopped moving. That is what this site is about.</p>
  <p>Japan's nocturnal food culture is unlike anywhere else on earth. The izakaya that only fills up after ten. The ramen cart that appears at midnight and vanishes by three. The conveyor-belt sushi counter where the last chefs are still cutting fish long after most restaurants have locked their doors. These are not consolation meals for people who missed dinner. They are the point.</p>
  <p>Yashoku is written by three people who came to this subject from different directions and share a conviction that the best meals in Japan happen after dark. No sponsored content. No hotel recommendations. The <a href="/rankings/">rankings</a> are personal and updated as we eat — not aggregated scores or press lists, just the places we would send someone we trust with no time to waste.</p>

  <h2>Contributors</h2>
  <p><strong>Hiroshi Nakamura</strong> is a food writer based between Tokyo and Osaka. He has spent the better part of a decade in the yakitori alleys under the Yamanote Line, in the standing bars of Shinjuku, and at yatai in Fukuoka. He covers izakaya culture, ramen, and the nocturnal street food circuits that don't make it into guidebooks.</p>
  <p><strong>Yuki Tanaka</strong> is based in Fukuoka and writes about regional cooking and street food across southern and western Japan. She is particularly interested in the ways local ingredients shape local identity — the Hakata bowl that can't be replicated in Tokyo, the Okinawan dish that has no equivalent anywhere else.</p>
  <p><strong>Kenji Mori</strong> is a former line cook turned restaurant critic. He writes about high-end Japanese cuisine, kaiseki, and the relationship between technique and restraint. He spent three years cooking in Kyoto before deciding he preferred eating to working.</p>

